[{"location":"#MVBernoulli","page":"Home","title":"MVBernoulli","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for MVBernoulli.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"#MVBernoulli.MultivariateBernoulli","page":"Home","title":"MVBernoulli.MultivariateBernoulli","text":"MultivariateBernoulli{T}\n\nA type for representing a multivariate Bernoulli distribution.\n\nFields\n\ntabulation::Vector{T}\nordinary_moments::Vector{T}\nnormalized_moments::Vector{T}\nm::Int: the number of variables\n\nDescription\n\nFor a multivariate Bernoulli distribution with m variables, the tabulation is a vector of length 2^m containing the probabilities of each of the possible outcomes.\n\nThe ordinary moments are the expected values of the variables and of their products.\n\nmathbbEleftprod_i in I X_iright\n\nwhere I is a subset of 1:m.\n\nThe normalized moments are\n\nmathbbEleftprod_i in I (X_i - mathbbEX_i)right\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#MVBernoulli.conditional_proba-Union{Tuple{By}, Tuple{Bx}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{MultivariateBernoulli{T}, Vector{Bx}, Vector{By}}} where {T, Bx, By}","page":"Home","title":"MVBernoulli.conditional_proba","text":"conditional probability of x given y. Missing values in y are considered as the unknown values, while\nmissing values in x are considered as not important. This means that if we consider the random variable X, and we set\nx = [1, missing, 0, missing] and y = [missing, 1, 0, missing], we are computing the conditional probability of X[1]=1 given X[2] = 1 and X[3] = 0.\n\nBy convention, if proba(y) = 0, then the conditional probability is 0.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
